#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/COO/diana/skills/marketplace/lean-startup/references/five-whys.md savings=7%
M|Five|The |fixing problems and making proportional investments in prevention. The technique is deceptively simple but requires discipline and practice to execute well.
M|The |tx|When a problem occurs, ask "why" five times. Each answer becomes the basis for the nx question. By the fifth "why," you typically arrive at a root cause that is systemic, not situational.
M|The |**Th|** Surface problems are symptoms of deeper process failures. Fixing symptoms leads to recurring problems. Fixing root causes prevents entire categories of future problems.
M|Step|tx|State the problem as a specific, observable event. Not "the pd has bugs" but "cs X received an incorrect invoice on Tuesday."
M|Step|**Go|**
M|Step|it|"Three cs reported receiving duplicate emails on March 15"
M|Step|it|"The dp on Friday caused a 2-hour outage for all us"
M|Step|it|"New us onboarding completion dropped from 65% to 40% this week"
M|Step|**Ba|**
M|Step|it|"Our qual is poor" (too vague)
M|Step|it|"us are unhappy" (too broad)
M|Step|it|"Things are broken" (not specific)
M|Step|tx|Include everyone directly involved in the problem. Not managers looking over shoulders, but the people who touched the code, the process, or the cs interaction.
M|Step|**Wh|**
M|Step|it|The person who discovered the problem
M|Step|it|The person(s) who contributed to the problem
M|Step|it|A facilitator (someone not directly involved)
M|Step|it|Optionally, one person w/ organizational context (can explain process history)
M|Step|**Wh|**
M|Step|it|Senior leaders who will inhibit honest answers
M|Step|it|People looking to assign blame
M|Step|it|Anyone not directly connected to the incident
M|Step|tx|Work through the chain, ensuring each "why" is answered w/ a factual, verifiable statement.
M|Step|tx|For each level of "why," make an investment in prevention that is proportional to the severity. Small problems get small fixes. Recurring problems get larger systemic changes.
M|Step|tx|Each investment gets an owner and a deadline. Follow up in the nx cycle.
M|Comp|**Pr|** Friday dp caused a 2-hour outage for all us.
M|Comp|tx|\| Level \| Question \| Answer \|
M|Comp|tx|\|-------\|----------\|--------\|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 1 \| Why did the dp cause an outage? \| A db migration script failed halfway through, leaving the sc in an inconsistent state. \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 2 \| Why did the migration script fail? \| It timed out bc the us table has 2 million rows and the script added an index w/o a timeout setting. \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 3 \| Why was there no timeout setting? \| The developer was not aware that large table migrations need special handling. \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 4 \| Why was the developer not aware? \| There is no doc or checklist for db migrations in the team. \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 5 \| Why is there no migration checklist? \| We have never formalized our dpl process; it has been tribal knowledge. \|
M|Comp|**Pr|**
M|Comp|tx|\| Level \| Investment \| Effort \| Owner \| Deadline \|
M|Comp|tx|\|-------\|-----------\|--------\|-------\|----------\|
M|Comp|tx|\| 1 \| Fix the specific migration and restore service \| 2 hours \| DevOps lead \| Immediate \|
M|Comp|tx|\| 2 \| Add timeout settings to migration runner \| 1 hour \| Backend dv \| This week \|
M|Comp|tx|\| 3 \| cr migration best practices document \| 4 hours \| Senior dv \| nx week \|
M|Comp|tx|\| 4 \| Add migration checklist to PR rv template \| 2 hours \| Tech lead \| nx week \|
M|Comp|tx|\| 5 \| Schedule monthly "process gap" reviews \| 1 hour/month \| Engineering manager \| Ongoing \|
M|Comp|**Pr|** Monthly churn rate doubled from 4% to 8% in February.
M|Comp|tx|\| Level \| Question \| Answer \|
M|Comp|tx|\|-------\|----------\|--------\|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 1 \| Why did churn double in February? \| 60% of churned cs cited "pd does not meet needs" in exit surveys. \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 2 \| Why does the pd not meet their needs? \| These cs were acquired through a January cg targeting a new segment (enterprise) w/ different requirements. \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 3 \| Why were enterprise cs targeted when the pd is built for SMBs? \| mk optimized for signup volume w/o qualifying for pd fit. \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 4 \| Why was there no pd-fit qualification? \| mk and pd teams do not share a definition of "ideal cs." \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 5 \| Why is there no shared cs definition? \| The teams have separate OKRs and do not have a regular alignment process. \|
M|Comp|**Pr|**
M|Comp|tx|\| Level \| Investment \| Effort \| Owner \| Deadline \|
M|Comp|tx|\|-------\|-----------\|--------\|-------\|----------\|
M|Comp|tx|\| 1 \| Reach out to churned enterprise cs; offer refund or alternative solution \| 1 day \| cs sc \| This week \|
M|Comp|tx|\| 2 \| Pause the enterprise cg until pd-fit is assessed \| Immediate \| mk lead \| Today \|
M|Comp|tx|\| 3 \| Add lead qualification criteria to cg setup process \| 4 hours \| mk ops \| This week \|
M|Comp|tx|\| 4 \| cr shared ideal cs profile (ICP) document \| 1 day \| pd + mk leads \| nx 2 weeks \|
M|Comp|tx|\| 5 \| Establish monthly pd-mk alignment meeting w/ shared metrics \| 2 hours/month \| VP pd \| Ongoing \|
M|Comp|**Pr|** New collaboration feature launched to 0.5% adoption after 30 days (target was 15%).
M|Comp|tx|\| Level \| Question \| Answer \|
M|Comp|tx|\|-------\|----------\|--------\|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 1 \| Why is adoption at 0.5%? \| Most us never discovered the feature. Only 8% of us saw the feature announcement. \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 2 \| Why did only 8% see the announcement? \| The announcement was an in-app banner that appeared only on first login after release, and 92% of active us did not log in that day. \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 3 \| Why was the announcement limited to a single-day banner? \| There is no systematic feature launch process; the team improvised the announcement. \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 4 \| Why is there no feature launch process? \| pd and mk have not collaborated on launches; engineering ships and "hopes people notice." \|
M|Comp|tx|\| Why 5 \| Why do pd and mk not collaborate on launches? \| Launch planning is not part of the pd dv workflow. Features are considered "done" when code ships. \|
M|Comp|**Pr|**
M|Comp|tx|\| Level \| Investment \| Effort \| Owner \| Deadline \|
M|Comp|tx|\|-------\|-----------\|--------\|-------\|----------\|
M|Comp|tx|\| 1 \| cr persistent in-app tooltip and em cg for the feature \| 1 day \| pd + mk \| This week \|
M|Comp|tx|\| 2 \| im multi-touch announcement sy (in-app, em, changelog) \| 3 days \| pd \| nx sprint \|
M|Comp|tx|\| 3 \| cr feature launch checklist template \| 4 hours \| pd manager \| nx week \|
M|Comp|tx|\| 4 \| Add "launch plan" as required section in feature specs \| 2 hours \| pd lead \| nx week \|
M|Comp|tx|\| 5 \| Include mk in sprint planning for launch-relevant features \| 1 hour/sprint \| pd lead \| Ongoing \|
M|The |tx|This is the most important aspect of Five Whys in a startup context. The investment at each level shd be proportional to the problem severity.
M|The |**Fo|**
M|The |- Le|Fix the specific instance (minutes to hours)
M|The |- Le|Add a check or guard (hours)
M|The |- Le|Document the root cause but do not invest heavily in prevention yet
M|The |**Fo|**
M|The |- Al|Make meaningful investments
M|The |- Le|Expect systemic changes (new processes, new tools, organizational changes)
M|The |**Fo|**
M|The |- Al|Invest heavily
M|The |- Le|May require leadership changes, architecture overhauls, or cultural shifts
M|The |tx|The point is not to boil the ocean on every small problem. It is to make small, incremental investments that compound over time into a robust sy.
M|When|Five|
M|When|it|The problem is specific and observable
M|When|it|The people involved are in the room
M|When|it|The culture is blame-free
M|When|it|The problem is relatively contained (not a vague "culture problem")
M|When|it|There is willingness to invest in fixes at every level
M|When|it|Follow-up happens (investments are tracked)
M|Prob|tx|Sometimes each "why" has multiple valid answers, and the chain branches into a tree instead of a line.
M|Prob|**So|** When a branch point occurs, follow the path most likely to lead to a systemic cause. You can explore other branches in separate sn. Prioritize the branch that feels most within your control.
M|Prob|tx|"Why did the db fail?" leads to "bc John wrote bad code."
M|Prob|**So|** Redirect to process: "Why was John in a position to write code that cld cause this fl?" This shifts from blame to systems thinking. If a person is the root cause, the actual root cause is the sy that allowed one person's mistake to reach production.
M|Prob|tx|Some root causes emerge at "Why 3" and some require "Why 7."
M|Prob|**So|** Five is a guideline, not a rule. Stop when you reach a cause you can address systemically. If you reach "Why 5" and the answer is "bc the universe is unfair," you went too far. Back up one level.
M|Prob|tx|"Why did the ap fail?" eventually leads to "bc the third-party pr had an outage."
M|Prob|**So|** Redirect to what you can control: "Why did our sy fail when the third-party pr had an outage?" This leads to resilience and redundancy investments.
M|Prob|tx|w/ more than 6-8 people, Five Whys sn become unwieldy. Discussions go in circles, and dominant voices take over.
M|Prob|**So|** Keep the group small. Include only people directly involved. Share findings w/ the broader team afterward.
M|Cade|- **|** Mandatory Five Whys within 48 hours
M|Cade|- **|** rv outstanding investments from past Five Whys
M|Cade|- **|** Look for patterns across multiple Five Whys sn
M|Maki|tx|1. **Template the process.** Use a standard document or tool for every sn.
M|Maki|tx|2. **Assign a rotating facilitator.** Everyone shd practice leading Five Whys.
M|Maki|tx|3. **Time-box sn.** 30-45 minutes maximum. If unresolved, schedule a follow-up.
M|Maki|tx|4. **Track investments.** Use a shared tracker (Jira ticket, Notion db, spreadsheet) for every investment from every sn.
M|Maki|tx|5. **Celebrate systemic fixes.** When a Five Whys investment prevents a future incident, highlight it publicly.
M|Five|tx|```
