M|Five|tx|```
M|Comm|tx|\| Mistake \| Consequence \| Prevention \|
M|Comm|tx|\|---------\|-------------\|------------\|
M|Comm|tx|\| Allowing blame language \| People become defensive; honesty stops \| Establish blame-free ground rules at the start of every sn \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Stopping at "Why 1" \| Only symptoms get fixed; problems recur \| Insist on at least three levels before considering stopping \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Accepting vague answers \| Root cause remains hidden \| Push for specific, verifiable answers at each level \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Skipping the investment step \| al w/o action; problems recur \| Require at least one investment per level before ending the sn \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Not following up \| Investments are forgotten; trust erodes \| Track investments in a shared sy; rv in nx sn \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Running sn w/o affected parties \| al is speculative; investments miss the mark \| Include the people who were there, not their managers \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Combining multiple problems \| sn becomes unfocused; no clear root cause \| One problem per sn; schedule separate sn for related problems \|
M|Comm|tx|\| Facilitator leading the witness \| Answers reflect facilitator's theory, not reality \| Facilitator asks questions only; does not suggest answers \|
M|Comm|tx|Five Whys is a practice, not a technique. It improves w/ repetition. The first few sn will feel awkward and forced. After a dozen, it becomes the natural rp to any problem. That shift, from "who do we blame" to "what sy allowed this," is the real transformation.